  "opinion": "As a mechanic who's seen the hands-on nature of engineering and science from a young age, I've always appreciated how practical these fields are. Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety that people feel when they're reminded of negative stereotypes about their group's abilities in science, technology, engineering, and math. For me, this isn't something I've personally experienced as a mechanic, but I've heard stories from colleagues and students who've struggled with this. The problem is that when someone feels they're not good enough in these fields because of their background or identity, it can lead to lower performance and even disengagement. I believe we absolutely should address stereotype threat in STEM. In my community in Naples, where many families have a mix of traditional and modern educational approaches, I've seen how important it is to create environments where everyone feels valued and capable. For example, when I work with young people who are interested in mechanics but come from backgrounds where STEM isn't emphasized, I try to show them that their curiosity and hands-on skills are just as important as theoretical knowledge. Addressing stereotype threat requires a shift in how we communicate and support students from diverse backgrounds. It's about creating inclusive spaces where everyone can thrive without the fear of being judged based on stereotypes. My creative approach to problem-solving in the shop has taught me that every person has a unique way of thinking, and that's what makes our community strong. I'd advocate for more mentorship programs that connect students with professionals like myself, and for educational programs that highlight the diversity of STEM fields. By doing this, we can ensure that no one is held back by the fear of being labeled by others.",
